\subsection{Atomic Skill Incremental Learning}
\label{sec:asil}
We maintain a growing library of atomic skills $\mathcal{S}_{k-1}=\{s_1,\dots,s_{M_{k-1}}\}$ before learning task $\mathcal{T}_k$, where each skill $s_m$ is a small parameter-efficient module (e.g., an adapter/LoRA block) with parameters $\theta_m$, and the frozen backbone has parameters $\theta_0$. For task $\mathcal{T}_k$, \texttt{TASER} first decides how many new skills to instantiate, then trains only the selected/new skill parameters under the current-data-only constraint. Concretely, we compute a task representation $r_k$ from task metadata (description) and/or a small batch of examples via a frozen encoder $E(\cdot)$, and measure its novelty against previously seen tasks $\{r_i\}_{i<k}$ by
\begin{equation}
d_k \;=\; \min_{i<k} \; d(r_k, r_i),
\end{equation}
where $d(\cdot,\cdot)$ can be cosine distance. We also estimate model uncertainty on $\mathcal{D}_k$ using a calibration-based score (placeholder choice consistent with the intro), e.g.,
\begin{equation}
u_k \;=\; \mathbb{E}_{(x,y)\sim \mathcal{D}_k}\big[\,1-\max_{y'} p_{\Theta_{k-1}}(y'\mid x)\,\big],
\end{equation}
where $\Theta_{k-1}=\{\theta_0,\theta_1,\dots,\theta_{M_{k-1}}\}$ denotes parameters after task $k{-}1$ and $p_{\Theta}$ is the task-conditional predictive distribution. We then allocate a task-specific number of new skills $n_k$ by a monotone policy $\pi(\cdot)$ that increases with novelty and uncertainty:
\begin{equation}
n_k \;=\; \pi(d_k,u_k) \;=\; \mathrm{clip}\Big(\Big\lceil \alpha d_k + \beta u_k \Big\rceil,\; 0,\; n_{\max}\Big),
\end{equation}
with hyperparameters $\alpha,\beta$ and per-task cap $n_{\max}$. We instantiate $\{s_{M_{k-1}+1},\dots,s_{M_{k-1}+n_k}\}$ (random init or from a standard initializer), yielding $\mathcal{S}_k=\mathcal{S}_{k-1}\cup\{s_{M_{k-1}+1},\dots,s_{M_{k-1}+n_k}\}$ and $M_k=M_{k-1}+n_k$.

Given an input $x$, the model prediction uses a gated composition of skills (defined in Sec.~\ref{sec:sdr}); during training on $\mathcal{T}_k$, we freeze $\theta_0$ and all old skills $\{\theta_m\}_{m\le M_{k-1}}$ (or optionally allow a small set to update; we keep the strict isolation setting as the default), and update only the newly added skills $\Theta_k^{\text{new}}=\{\theta_m\}_{m=M_{k-1}+1}^{M_k}$ and the router parameters $\phi$ by minimizing the task loss:
\begin{equation}
\min_{\Theta_k^{\text{new}},\,\phi}\;\; 
\mathbb{E}_{(x,y)\sim \mathcal{D}_k}\Big[\mathcal{L}_k\big(f(x;\theta_0,\{\theta_m\}_{m\le M_k},\phi),y\big)\Big]
\;+\;\lambda_{\text{ortho}}\mathcal{R}_{\text{ortho}},
\label{eq:task_obj}
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{L}_k$ matches the task output structure (classification/extraction/generation) and $\mathcal{R}_{\text{ortho}}$ is the orthogonality regularizer introduced next. This incremental expansion ensures sufficient new capacity for highly divergent tasks while preserving prior skills by construction (no raw past data required).

\subsection{Orthogonality-enhanced Skill Detection}
\label{sec:oesd}
A key requirement in high-heterogeneity continual learning is to keep skills \emph{atomic}: each skill should encode a distinct and reusable function rather than drifting into entangled, overlapping representations that increase interference. \texttt{TASER} enforces this via an orthogonality-enhanced skill detection objective that (i) encourages parameter- or representation-level separation among skills and (ii) provides a signal to detect redundancy during/after training.

\paragraph{Orthogonality regularization.}
Let $v_m \in \mathbb{R}^P$ denote a vectorized (or projected) representation of skill $s_m$ (e.g., concatenated adapter weights, or the output activation statistics of the skill on current-task data). We define a normalized skill vector $\bar{v}_m = v_m/\|v_m\|_2$ and penalize correlations between skill pairs:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}_{\text{ortho}}
\;=\;
\sum_{m\neq n} \big(\bar{v}_m^\top \bar{v}_n\big)^2
\;=\;
\big\| \bar{V}^\top \bar{V} - I \big\|_F^2,
\label{eq:ortho}
\end{equation}
where $\bar{V}=[\bar{v}_1,\dots,\bar{v}_{M_k}]$ and $I$ is the identity. In practice, we apply Eq.~\eqref{eq:ortho} to (a) new-vs-old pairs to prevent the newly added skills from collapsing onto existing ones, and (b) new-vs-new pairs to diversify the newly instantiated set for $\mathcal{T}_k$. This regularizer is added to the per-task objective in Eq.~\eqref{eq:task_obj} with weight $\lambda_{\text{ortho}}$.

\paragraph{Skill detection and redundancy control.}
To detect whether a newly created skill is truly novel or redundant, we compute its maximum similarity to existing skills after (or during) training:
\begin{equation}
\rho_m \;=\; \max_{n < m} \; \big|\bar{v}_m^\top \bar{v}_n\big|.
\end{equation}
A high $\rho_m$ indicates that skill $m$ overlaps strongly with a prior skill, violating atomicity. We use this signal to (optionally) (i) reinitialize the redundant skill and retrain, (ii) drop it from $\mathcal{S}_k$, or (iii) increase $\lambda_{\text{ortho}}$ adaptively for subsequent steps:
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{\text{ortho}} \leftarrow \lambda_{\text{ortho}} \cdot \big(1 + \gamma \cdot \mathbb{I}[\rho_m>\tau]\big),
\end{equation}
with threshold $\tau$ and factor $\gamma$. This ``detection + orthogonality'' mechanism ensures the skill library grows with diverse, non-overlapping functional modules, improving reuse and reducing interference under highly heterogeneous task streams.

\subsection{Skill Dynamic Routing}
\label{sec:sdr}
Given a library of atomic skills, \texttt{TASER} must decide \emph{which} skills to activate for each task and \emph{how} to compose them, enabling both specialization (new tasks) and reuse (shared sub-skills) without retraining the entire model. We adopt a lightweight, task-conditioned gating router that outputs sparse routing weights over skills.

\paragraph{Task-conditioned gating.}
For each task $\mathcal{T}_k$, we compute a task identity embedding $r_k$ (the same representation used for divergence), and a router $g_\phi$ produces logits over skills:
\begin{equation}
\ell_k \;=\; g_\phi(r_k) \in \mathbb{R}^{M_k},
\qquad
w_k \;=\; \mathrm{softmax}(\ell_k).
\label{eq:gating}
\end{equation}
To encourage sparse composition (few active skills), we use a top-$L$ masking operator:
\begin{equation}
\tilde{w}_{k,m} \;=\;
\begin{cases}
\displaystyle \frac{\exp(\ell_{k,m})}{\sum_{j\in \mathrm{TopL}(\ell_k)} \exp(\ell_{k,j})}, & m\in \mathrm{TopL}(\ell_k),\\[6pt]
0, & \text{otherwise},
\end{cases}
\label{eq:topl}
\end{equation}
where $\mathrm{TopL}(\ell_k)$ returns indices of the $L$ largest logits. This yields a deterministic, interpretable selection of active skills for each task.

\paragraph{Skill composition in the forward pass.}
Let $h(x;\theta_0)$ be the backbone hidden representation (or the sequence of layer activations for LMs). Each skill $s_m$ produces a modulation $\Delta_m(x)$ (e.g., an adapter output) applied at designated layers. The routed model output is computed by a weighted sum of skill contributions:
\begin{equation}
\Delta(x) \;=\; \sum_{m=1}^{M_k} \tilde{w}_{k,m}\,\Delta_m(x),
\qquad
f(x) \;=\; \mathrm{Head}\big(h(x;\theta_0) + \Delta(x)\big),
\label{eq:compose}
\end{equation}
where $\mathrm{Head}(\cdot)$ maps to the task-specific output space (classification logits, extracted spans, or generation probabilities). Because $\tilde{w}_k$ depends only on $r_k$ (task identity) rather than labels, routing is stable and can be used at inference time without additional adaptation.

\paragraph{Training the router.}
During task $\mathcal{T}_k$, we train router parameters $\phi$ jointly with new skills by backpropagating the task loss through Eqs.~\eqref{eq:gating}--\eqref{eq:compose}. To prevent the router from trivially activating many skills, we add a sparsity regularizer (one simple option) on the gating distribution:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}_{\text{sparse}} \;=\; \| \tilde{w}_k \|_1 \;\;(\text{constant under normalization})\;\;\text{or}\;\; 
\mathcal{R}_{\text{sparse}} \;=\; -H(\tilde{w}_k),
\end{equation}
and in practice we primarily rely on the hard top-$L$ constraint in Eq.~\eqref{eq:topl}. Overall, dynamic routing allows \texttt{TASER} to (i) reuse previously learned atomic skills when beneficial (low $d_k$, low $u_k$), (ii) exploit newly expanded capacity for divergent tasks (high $d_k$, high $u_k$), and (iii) maintain modularity and interpretability by producing task-wise sparse skill compositions.
