```latex
\subsection{Atomic Skill Incremental Learning}
\label{sec:asil}
\texttt{TASER} maintains a growing library of atomic skills implemented as parameter-efficient adapters (e.g., LoRA). Let the backbone parameters be frozen as $\theta_0$, and let the current skill library before task $\mathcal{T}_k$ be $\mathcal{S}_{k-1}=\{s_1,\dots,s_{M_{k-1}}\}$, where each skill corresponds to a LoRA module with parameters $\theta_m=\{A_m,B_m\}$ (we omit layer indices for clarity). Upon receiving a new task $\mathcal{T}_k$, the key decision is \emph{how much new capacity to allocate}. Unlike using a fixed rank, we dynamically determine the number/dimension of new atomic skills by estimating the \emph{novel subspace} of $\mathcal{T}_k$ relative to the historical skill subspace, using a three-step procedure (Fig.~\ref{fig:framework}A). Intuitively, highly heterogeneous tasks (large divergence) require larger novel subspaces and thus more new skill capacity, while related tasks can be handled by reusing existing skills through routing (Sec.~\ref{sec:sdr}).

\paragraph{Step A: Rapid subspace probing.}
We first fit a temporary high-rank probe LoRA on the current-task data to capture the dominant update directions of $\mathcal{T}_k$. Concretely, we instantiate a probe module with rank $r_{\text{probe}}$ (e.g., 32),
$\theta_{\text{probe}}=\{A_{\text{probe}},B_{\text{probe}}\}$,
and perform a short warm-up training on $(x,y)\sim\mathcal{D}_k$ while keeping $\theta_0$ and all historical skills fixed. This probe is \emph{not} meant to converge; instead, a few steps are sufficient to stabilize the singular spectrum of $A_{\text{probe}}$, which we treat as an empirical sketch of the task-induced subspace.

\paragraph{Step B: Orthogonal complement w.r.t.\ historical skill subspace.}
To isolate what cannot be explained by previously learned skills, we define the historical down-projection matrix by concatenating (row-wise) the down projections of all existing skills:
\begin{equation}
A_{\text{hist}} = \mathrm{Concat}\big(A_1,\dots,A_{M_{k-1}}\big).
\end{equation}
Let $Q_{\text{hist}}$ be an orthonormal basis of the row-span of $A_{\text{hist}}$ obtained via QR decomposition (equivalently, any orthonormal basis of the historical skill subspace). We project the probe onto the orthogonal complement of the historical subspace to obtain the residual matrix:
\begin{equation}
A_{\text{diff}}
\;=\;
A_{\text{probe}}\big(I - Q_{\text{hist}}^{\top}Q_{\text{hist}}\big),
\label{eq:adiff}
\end{equation}
where $A_{\text{diff}}$ represents the \emph{novel} feature components required by $\mathcal{T}_k$ that are not spanned by existing skills. This step aligns with \texttt{TASER}'s goal under high heterogeneity: expand capacity only along directions that are orthogonal to (hence minimally interfering with) the accumulated skills.

\paragraph{Step C: SVD-based dynamic rank (new skill dimension) determination.}
We perform SVD on $A_{\text{diff}}$,
\begin{equation}
A_{\text{diff}} = U\Sigma V^{\top}, \qquad \Sigma=\mathrm{diag}(\sigma_1,\sigma_2,\dots),
\end{equation}
and choose the minimal rank that covers a target fraction of spectral energy:
\begin{equation}
r_{\text{new}}
=
\min\left\{
t \;\middle|\;
\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{t}\sigma_i}{\sum_{j}\sigma_j}\ge \theta_{\text{energy}}
\right\},
\label{eq:rnew}
\end{equation}
where $\theta_{\text{energy}}\in(0,1)$ (e.g., 0.9). We then instantiate the formal new skill(s) for $\mathcal{T}_k$ with total dimension $r_{\text{new}}$ (implemented as one LoRA of rank $r_{\text{new}}$ or equivalently multiple smaller atomic skills whose ranks sum to $r_{\text{new}}$; we use \texttt{XXX} in implementation). The new skill parameters $\theta^{\text{new}}_k$ are initialized from the leading singular directions (e.g., using the top-$r_{\text{new}}$ components from $U,\Sigma,V$) or standard initialization, and are trained on $\mathcal{D}_k$ together with the router (Sec.~\ref{sec:sdr}) under the current-data-only constraint:
\begin{equation}
\min_{\theta^{\text{new}}_k,\,\phi}\;
\mathbb{E}_{(x,y)\sim\mathcal{D}_k}
\Big[
\mathcal{L}_k\big(f(x;\theta_0,\mathcal{S}_{k-1}\cup \theta^{\text{new}}_k,\phi),y\big)
\Big],
\end{equation}
with $\theta_0$ and all historical skill parameters frozen. This dynamic, geometry-driven allocation directly addresses the rigid capacity issue highlighted in the Introduction: tasks with low semantic overlap induce larger $A_{\text{diff}}$ energy and thus larger $r_{\text{new}}$, while related tasks lead to small (or even near-zero) incremental capacity and rely more on skill reuse via routing.
