\subsection{Atomic Skill Incremental Learning}
\label{sec:asil}
\texttt{TASER} maintains a growing library of atomic skills implemented as parameter efficient adapters (e.g., LoRA). Let the backbone parameters be frozen as $\theta_0$. Before learning task $\mathcal{T}_k$, the skill library is $\mathcal{S}_{k-1}=\{s_1,\dots,s_{M_{k-1}}\}$, where each skill $s_m$ is parameterized by $\theta_m=\{A_m,B_m\}$ (layer indices are omitted for clarity). Under high task heterogeneity, a fixed capacity allocation is often either insufficient for divergent tasks or wasteful for related ones. Therefore, for each incoming task $\mathcal{T}_k$, \texttt{TASER} dynamically allocates new skill capacity by estimating the novel subspace induced by $\mathcal{D}_k$ relative to the historical skill subspace. The procedure consists of three steps.

\paragraph{Step A: Rapid subspace probing.}
We first train a temporary probe LoRA with a sufficiently large rank $r_{\text{probe}}$ to capture dominant update directions of $\mathcal{T}_k$. Concretely, we instantiate $\theta_{\text{probe}}=\{A_{\text{probe}},B_{\text{probe}}\}$ with rank $r_{\text{probe}}$ and run a short warm up optimization on current task samples $(x,y)\sim\mathcal{D}_k$, while keeping $\theta_0$ and all historical skills in $\mathcal{S}_{k-1}$ frozen. This probe is not required to converge. Its goal is to obtain a stable singular spectrum that reflects the principal subspace of task induced gradients.

\paragraph{Step B: Novel subspace via orthogonal complement to historical skills.}
To identify components that cannot be explained by existing skills, we form the historical down projection matrix by concatenating the down projections of all previous skills:
\begin{equation}
A_{\text{hist}} = \mathrm{Concat}\big(A_1,\dots,A_{M_{k-1}}\big).
\end{equation}
Let $Q_{\text{hist}}$ denote an orthonormal basis of the row span of $A_{\text{hist}}$, obtained via QR decomposition (or any equivalent orthogonalization). We then project the probe matrix onto the orthogonal complement of the historical subspace:
\begin{equation}
A_{\text{diff}}
=
A_{\text{probe}}
\big(I - Q_{\text{hist}}^{\top}Q_{\text{hist}}\big),
\label{eq:adiff}
\end{equation}
where $A_{\text{diff}}$ represents novel feature components required by $\mathcal{T}_k$ that are not spanned by the accumulated skill space. This geometry based separation matches \texttt{TASER}'s objective of expanding capacity only along minimally interfering directions under the current data only constraint.

\paragraph{Step C: SVD based rank determination for new skills.}
We perform singular value decomposition on the residual matrix:
\begin{equation}
A_{\text{diff}} = U\Sigma V^{\top}, 
\qquad
\Sigma=\mathrm{diag}(\sigma_1,\sigma_2,\dots).
\end{equation}
We choose the minimal rank that covers a target fraction of spectral energy:
\begin{equation}
r_{\text{new}}
=
\min\left\{
t \;\middle|\;
\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{t}\sigma_i}{\sum_{j}\sigma_j}\ge \theta_{\text{energy}}
\right\},
\label{eq:rnew}
\end{equation}
where $\theta_{\text{energy}}\in(0,1)$ is an energy coverage threshold. We then instantiate the new skill capacity for $\mathcal{T}_k$ with total rank $r_{\text{new}}$, yielding updated library $\mathcal{S}_k=\mathcal{S}_{k-1}\cup \mathcal{S}^{\text{new}}_k$ and $M_k=M_{k-1}+|\mathcal{S}^{\text{new}}_k|$. In implementation, this capacity can be realized as one LoRA module of rank $r_{\text{new}}$ or multiple smaller atomic skills whose ranks sum to $r_{\text{new}}$.

Finally, we train only the newly instantiated skill parameters and the router parameters $\phi$ (Sec.~\ref{sec:sdr}) on $\mathcal{D}_k$, with the backbone $\theta_0$ and all historical skill parameters frozen:
\begin{equation}
\min_{\theta^{\text{new}}_k,\,\phi}\;
\mathbb{E}_{(x,y)\sim\mathcal{D}_k}
\Big[
\mathcal{L}_k\big(f(x;\theta_0,\mathcal{S}_{k-1}\cup \mathcal{S}^{\text{new}}_k,\phi),y\big)
\Big].
\end{equation}
This dynamic allocation rule directly supports the high heterogeneity setting described in the Introduction: when the new task lies far from the historical skill space, $A_{\text{diff}}$ has higher residual energy and yields a larger $r_{\text{new}}$, while related tasks induce a small residual and thus rely more on skill reuse through routing.
