\subsection{Skill Dynamic Routing}
\label{sec:sdr}
As \texttt{TASER} incrementally expands a library of atomic skills, activating all skills for every input becomes computationally inefficient and may introduce interference, especially under high task heterogeneity. We therefore propose \emph{Skill Dynamic Routing}, a lightweight gating mechanism that selects and composes a sparse subset of skills conditioned on the current input, enabling both task specific specialization and cross task reuse.

\paragraph{Routing formulation.}
We implement each atomic skill as a LoRA style update and keep the backbone frozen. For a given transformer layer (indices omitted for clarity), let $W_0$ denote the frozen backbone linear map and let the historical skill bank before learning $\mathcal{T}_k$ be
\begin{equation}
A_{\text{hist}} = \mathrm{Concat}(A_1,\dots,A_{M_{k-1}}),
\qquad
B_{\text{hist}} = \mathrm{Concat}(B_1,\dots,B_{M_{k-1}}),
\end{equation}
where $M_{k-1}$ is the number of accumulated skills. Given an input activation vector $x$, the router $R_\phi$ outputs a multi skill gating vector $\boldsymbol{\alpha}(x)\in[0,1]^{M_{k-1}}$, and the routed layer output is computed as
\begin{equation}
h_{\text{out}}
=
W_0 x
+
B_{\text{hist}}
\Big(
\boldsymbol{\alpha}(x) \odot (A_{\text{hist}}x)
\Big),
\label{eq:dsr_forward}
\end{equation}
where $\odot$ is the Hadamard product. Eq.~\eqref{eq:dsr_forward} can be viewed as an input dependent selection of historical atomic skills, where $\alpha_m(x)$ amplifies or suppresses the contribution of skill $m$. We use a Sigmoid gate rather than Softmax since multiple skills can be simultaneously helpful for a heterogeneous task.

\paragraph{Router architecture.}
The router is designed to be lightweight so that routing does not dominate computation. Specifically, we use a two layer MLP with a bottleneck:
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\alpha}(x)
=
\sigma\Big(
W_2\,\mathrm{ReLU}(W_1 x + b_1) + b_2
\Big),
\label{eq:router}
\end{equation}
where $\phi=\{W_1,b_1,W_2,b_2\}$ are router parameters and the hidden dimension is reduced by a bottleneck ratio $r_{\text{ratio}}$ (e.g., $4$). This design supports multi skill activation while keeping the routing module parameter efficient.

\paragraph{Training strategy with sparsity regularization.}
To ensure interference free retrieval from the skill library, we train routing under a frozen backbone and a frozen historical skill bank. Concretely, during the routing optimization phase, we freeze $\theta_0$ and all historical skills in $\mathcal{S}_{k-1}$ (equivalently $A_{\text{hist}},B_{\text{hist}}), and update only $\phi$ by minimizing
\begin{equation}
\min_{\phi}\;
\mathbb{E}_{(x,y)\sim\mathcal{D}_k}
\Big[
\mathcal{L}_k\big(f(x;\theta_0,\mathcal{S}_{k-1},\phi),y\big)
\Big]
+
\lambda_{\text{sparse}}
\,
\|\boldsymbol{\alpha}(x)\|_1,
\label{eq:router_obj}
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{L}_k(\cdot)$ matches the output structure of task $\mathcal{T}_k$ and $\lambda_{\text{sparse}}$ controls sparsity. The $L_1$ penalty encourages the router to activate only the minimal set of relevant atomic skills for each input, improving efficiency and reducing noise from unrelated skills. This dynamic routing mechanism is essential in \texttt{TASER} for handling highly heterogeneous task streams, where different inputs within the same task may require different mixtures of reusable capabilities.
